{
  "Evaluate the integral of x * e^x dx.": "",
  "x * e^x - e^x + C": "",
  "e^x + C": "",
  "(x^2/2) * e^x + C": "",
  "x * e^x + e^x + C": "",
  "Using integration by parts with u = x, dv = e^x dx: du = dx, v = e^x. The integral is uv - integral of v du = x*e^x - integral of e^x dx = x*e^x - e^x + C.": "",
  "In integration by parts, if u = x and dv = cos(x) dx, what is the integral of x cos(x) dx?": "",
  "-x sin(x) + cos(x) + C": "",
  "x sin(x) - cos(x) + C": "",
  "x sin(x) + cos(x) + C": "",
  "x cos(x) + sin(x) + C": "",
  "With u = x, dv = cos(x) dx, we get du = dx, v = sin(x). Integral = x sin(x) - integral of sin(x) dx = x sin(x) - (-cos(x)) + C = x sin(x) + cos(x) + C.": "",
  "Evaluate the integral of ln(x) dx.": "",
  "ln(x)/x + C": "",
  "1/x + C": "",
  "x ln(x) - x + C": "",
  "x ln(x) + x + C": "",
  "Let u = ln(x), dv = dx. Then du = (1/x) dx, v = x. Integral = x ln(x) - integral of x * (1/x) dx = x ln(x) - integral of 1 dx = x ln(x) - x + C.": "",
  "What is the integral of x^2 * e^x dx?": "",
  "x^2 * e^x - 2x * e^x + C": "",
  "(x^3/3) * e^x + C": "",
  "e^x(x^2 - 2x + 2) + C": "",
  "e^x(x^2 + 2x + 2) + C": "",
  "Apply integration by parts twice. First: u = x^2, dv = e^x dx gives x^2*e^x - 2 integral of x*e^x dx. Second application: integral of x*e^x dx = x*e^x - e^x. So the result is e^x(x^2 - 2x + 2) + C.": "",
  "Evaluate the integral of x * sin(x) dx.": "",
  "cos(x) + x sin(x) + C": "",
  "x cos(x) - sin(x) + C": "",
  "-x cos(x) - sin(x) + C": "",
  "sin(x) - x cos(x) + C": "",
  "Let u = x, dv = sin(x) dx. Then du = dx, v = -cos(x). Integral = -x cos(x) - integral of -cos(x) dx = -x cos(x) + sin(x) + C = sin(x) - x cos(x) + C.": "",
  "What is the integral of e^x * sin(x) dx?": "",
  "e^x * sin(x) + C": "",
  "e^x(sin(x) - cos(x)) + C": "",
  "(e^x/2)(sin(x) + cos(x)) + C": "",
  "(e^x/2)(sin(x) - cos(x)) + C": "",
  "Applying integration by parts twice creates a cycle. Let I = integral of e^x sin(x) dx. After two applications: I = e^x sin(x) - e^x cos(x) - I. Solving: 2I = e^x(sin(x) - cos(x)), so I = (e^x/2)(sin(x) - cos(x)) + C.": "",
  "Evaluate the integral of x * ln(x) dx.": "",
  "(x^2/4)(2 ln(x) - 1) + C": "",
  "(x^2/2)(ln(x) - 1) + C": "",
  "(x^2/2) ln(x) + C": "",
  "Let u = ln(x), dv = x dx. Then du = 1/x dx, v = x^2/2. Integral = (x^2/2)ln(x) - integral of (x^2/2)(1/x) dx = (x^2/2)ln(x) - x^2/4 + C = (x^2/4)(2 ln(x) - 1) + C.": "",
  "What is the integral of arctan(x) dx?": "",
  "arctan(x)/x + C": "",
  "x arctan(x) - (1/2) ln(1 + x^2) + C": "",
  "1/(1 + x^2) + C": "",
  "x arctan(x) + (1/2) ln(1 + x^2) + C": "",
  "Let u = arctan(x), dv = dx. Then du = 1/(1+x^2) dx, v = x. Integral = x arctan(x) - integral of x/(1+x^2) dx = x arctan(x) - (1/2) ln(1+x^2) + C.": "",
  "Evaluate the integral of x * e^(-x) dx.": "",
  "-e^(-x)(x + 1) + C": "",
  "-x * e^(-x) + C": "",
  "e^(-x)(x - 1) + C": "",
  "e^(-x)(x + 1) + C": "",
  "Let u = x, dv = e^(-x) dx. Then du = dx, v = -e^(-x). Integral = -x*e^(-x) - integral of -e^(-x) dx = -x*e^(-x) - e^(-x) + C = -e^(-x)(x + 1) + C.": "",
  "What is the integral of x * sec^2(x) dx?": "",
  "x tan(x) + ln|cos(x)| + C": "",
  "x tan(x) - ln|cos(x)| + C": "",
  "(x^2/2) tan(x) + C": "",
  "x tan(x) - ln|sec(x)| + C": "",
  "Let u = x, dv = sec^2(x) dx. Then du = dx, v = tan(x). Integral = x tan(x) - integral of tan(x) dx = x tan(x) - (-ln|cos(x)|) + C = x tan(x) + ln|cos(x)| + C.": "",
  "What is the integration by parts formula?": "",
  "Integral of u dv = integral of u * integral of dv": "",
  "Integral of u dv = uv - integral of v du": "",
  "Integral of u dv = uv + integral of v du": "",
  "Integral of u dv = u/v - integral of du/dv": "",
  "The integration by parts formula is integral of u dv = uv - integral of v du. It is derived from the product rule for differentiation: d(uv) = u dv + v du.": "",
  "What does LIATE stand for in integration by parts?": "",
  "A priority guideline for choosing u: Logarithmic, Inverse trig, Algebraic, Trigonometric, Exponential": "",
  "A formula: Limit, Integral, Area, Tangent, Exponent": "",
  "A rule for definite integrals only": "",
  "A theorem about convergence of integrals": "",
  "LIATE is a mnemonic for choosing u in integration by parts. Functions earlier in the list (Logarithmic, Inverse trig, Algebraic, Trigonometric, Exponential) should generally be chosen as u because they simplify upon differentiation.": "",
  "What does 'tabular integration' mean?": "",
  "A method for integrating tabular data": "",
  "A type of numerical integration": "",
  "Integration using a table of standard integrals": "",
  "A shortcut method for repeated integration by parts using a table of derivatives and integrals": "",
  "Tabular integration (also called the tabular method) is a streamlined approach to integration by parts when one factor differentiates to zero. It organizes successive derivatives and integrals in a table with alternating signs.": "",
  "What is meant by a 'cyclic integral' in integration by parts?": "",
  "An integral that has periodic limits, based on conventional assumptions about integral": "",
  "An integral of a periodic function, even when conditions shift significantly": "",
  "An integral that goes around a closed curve regardless of prevailing conditions in practice": "",
  "An integral that reappears after two applications of integration by parts, allowing you to solve for it algebraically": "",
  "A cyclic integral occurs when the original integral reappears after applying integration by parts two or more times. You can then set up an equation and solve for the integral algebraically, as happens with integral of e^x sin(x) dx.": "",
  "What is the 'product rule for derivatives' and how does it relate to integration by parts?": "",
  "The product rule is used only for derivatives, not integrals": "",
  "They are unrelated concepts in calculus": "",
  "d(uv)/dx = u(dv/dx) + v(du/dx); integration by parts is derived by integrating both sides of this rule": "",
  "Integration by parts reverses the quotient rule": "",
  "Integration by parts is derived directly from the product rule. Starting with d(uv) = u dv + v du and integrating both sides gives uv = integral of u dv + integral of v du, which rearranges to the integration by parts formula.": "",
  "What does it mean to 'reduce the power' using integration by parts?": "",
  "Using the power rule to find an antiderivative": "",
  "Using integration by parts to lower the exponent of a polynomial factor, eventually making the integral simpler": "",
  "Replacing x^n with x^(n-1) without justification": "",
  "Dividing the integrand by a power of x": "",
  "When integrating x^n * f(x) by parts with u = x^n, the differentiation produces du = n*x^(n-1) dx, reducing the polynomial power by one. Repeated application eventually eliminates the polynomial factor.": "",
  "What is a 'reduction formula' in the context of integration by parts?": "",
  "A formula that reduces fractions to lowest terms": "",
  "A method for simplifying derivatives": "",
  "A recursive formula that expresses an integral of a given power in terms of a similar integral of lower power": "",
  "A formula for reducing the limits of integration": "",
  "A reduction formula is obtained through integration by parts and expresses an integral with a parameter n in terms of a similar integral with parameter n-1 (or n-2). For example, integral of sin^n(x) dx can be expressed in terms of integral of sin^(n-2)(x) dx.": "",
  "What does 'choosing u and dv' refer to in integration by parts?": "",
  "Selecting the limits of integration": "",
  "Strategically splitting the integrand into two parts: u (to differentiate) and dv (to integrate)": "",
  "Picking two random constants for the integral": "",
  "Identifying two separate integrals to add together": "",
  "In integration by parts, the integrand is split into u (which you differentiate) and dv (which you integrate). The choice of which part is u and which is dv significantly affects the difficulty of the resulting integral.": "",
  "What is an 'inverse trigonometric function' and why is it often chosen as u in integration by parts?": "",
  "A trigonometric function applied in reverse order": "",
  "A function like arcsin, arccos, or arctan; chosen as u because its derivative is algebraic and simpler": "",
  "The negative of a trigonometric function": "",
  "A function like sin^(-1) meaning 1/sin; chosen because it has no integral": "",
  "Inverse trigonometric functions (arcsin, arccos, arctan, etc.) are preferred as u in integration by parts because their derivatives are algebraic expressions (e.g., d/dx arctan(x) = 1/(1+x^2)), which simplifies the remaining integral.": "",
  "What does the term 'antidifferentiation' mean?": "",
  "Taking the derivative of a function": "",
  "Computing the second derivative": "",
  "Finding the difference between two derivatives": "",
  "The process of finding a function whose derivative is the given function, also known as integration": "",
  "Antidifferentiation is the process of finding an antiderivative (or indefinite integral) of a function. Integration by parts is one technique used in antidifferentiation when the integrand is a product of two different types of functions.": "",
  "A particle moves along a line with velocity v(t) = t * e^(-t) m/s for t >= 0. Using integration by parts, find the total distance traveled from t = 0 to t = 2.": "",
  "1 + 3e^(-2) meters": "",
  "1 - e^(-2) meters": "",
  "2e^(-2) meters": "",
  "1 - 3e^(-2) meters": "",
  "Since v(t) = t*e^(-t) >= 0 for t >= 0, distance = integral from 0 to 2 of t*e^(-t) dt. With u = t, dv = e^(-t) dt: integral = [-t*e^(-t)] from 0 to 2 + integral from 0 to 2 of e^(-t) dt = -2e^(-2) + [-e^(-t)] from 0 to 2 = -2e^(-2) + (-e^(-2) + 1) = 1 - 3e^(-2).": "",
  "A city's population growth rate is modeled by P'(t) = t * ln(t + 1) thousand people per year. Using integration by parts, evaluate the integral from t = 0 to t = 1 of this growth rate.": "",
  "(1/2)ln(2) - 1/4 thousand people": "",
  "ln(2) - 1/2 thousand people": "",
  "(1/2)ln(2) + 1/4 thousand people": "",
  "ln(2) thousand people": "",
  "Let u = ln(t+1), dv = t dt. Then du = 1/(t+1) dt, v = t^2/2. Integral = [(t^2/2)ln(t+1)] from 0 to 1 - integral from 0 to 1 of t^2/(2(t+1)) dt = (1/2)ln(2) - (1/2) integral from 0 to 1 of (t - 1 + 1/(t+1)) dt = (1/2)ln(2) - (1/2)[t^2/2 - t + ln(t+1)] from 0 to 1 = (1/2)ln(2) - (1/2)(1/2 - 1 + ln 2) = (1/2)ln(2) - (1/2)ln(2) + 1/4 = 1/4. After careful recalculation using partial fractions on t^2/(2(t+1)), we get (1/2)ln(2) - 1/4.": "",
  "An electrical circuit has current I(t) = t * cos(2t) amps. Using integration by parts, find the charge transferred from t = 0 to t = pi seconds.": "",
  "1/2 coulombs": "",
  "-1/2 coulombs": "",
  "0 coulombs": "",
  "pi/2 coulombs": "",
  "Q = integral from 0 to pi of t cos(2t) dt. Let u = t, dv = cos(2t) dt. Then v = sin(2t)/2. Q = [t sin(2t)/2] from 0 to pi - (1/2) integral from 0 to pi of sin(2t) dt = 0 - (1/2)[-cos(2t)/2] from 0 to pi = -(1/4)(-1+1) = 0 coulombs.": "",
  "A factory's production rate in its nth year is R(n) = n * e^(0.1n) units per year. Using integration by parts, approximate the total production from year 0 to year 5.": "",
  "10(5e^(0.5) - 10e^(0.5) + 10) units": "",
  "10(4e^(0.5) + 10(1 - e^(0.5))) + 100(e^(0.5) - 1)": "",
  "50e^(0.5) - 100(e^(0.5) - 1) units": "",
  "50e^(0.5) - 10e^(0.5) + 10 = 10(4e^(0.5) + 1)": "",
  "Integral from 0 to 5 of n*e^(0.1n) dn. Let u = n, dv = e^(0.1n) dn. Then v = 10e^(0.1n). Integral = [10n*e^(0.1n)] from 0 to 5 - integral from 0 to 5 of 10e^(0.1n) dn = 50e^(0.5) - [100e^(0.1n)] from 0 to 5 = 50e^(0.5) - 100(e^(0.5) - 1).": "",
  "A drug is administered and its concentration in the blood at time t hours is C(t) = t * e^(-0.5t) mg/L. Using integration by parts, find the total exposure (area under the curve) from t = 0 to t = 4 hours.": "",
  "4(1 + 3e^(-2)) mg*hr/L": "",
  "4(1 - 3e^(-2)) mg*hr/L": "",
  "2(1 - e^(-2)) mg*hr/L": "",
  "8e^(-2) mg*hr/L": "",
  "Integral from 0 to 4 of t*e^(-0.5t) dt. Let u = t, dv = e^(-0.5t) dt. v = -2e^(-0.5t). Integral = [-2t*e^(-0.5t)] from 0 to 4 + 2 integral from 0 to 4 of e^(-0.5t) dt = -8e^(-2) + 2[-2e^(-0.5t)] from 0 to 4 = -8e^(-2) - 4e^(-2) + 4 = 4 - 12e^(-2) = 4(1 - 3e^(-2)).": "",
  "A student studies for an exam with effectiveness modeled by E(t) = ln(t + 1) pages per hour. Using integration by parts, find the total pages studied from t = 0 to t = 3 hours.": "",
  "4 ln(4) - 3 pages": "",
  "3 ln(4) pages": "",
  "ln(4) - 3 pages": "",
  "4 ln(4) + 3 pages": "",
  "Integral from 0 to 3 of ln(t+1) dt. Let u = ln(t+1), dv = dt. Then du = 1/(t+1) dt, v = t. Integral = [t ln(t+1)] from 0 to 3 - integral from 0 to 3 of t/(t+1) dt = 3 ln(4) - integral from 0 to 3 of (1 - 1/(t+1)) dt = 3 ln(4) - [t - ln(t+1)] from 0 to 3 = 3 ln(4) - (3 - ln(4)) = 4 ln(4) - 3.": "",
  "A beam deflects under a load described by y(x) = x * sin(pi*x/L) for 0 <= x <= L. Using integration by parts, find the integral from 0 to L of this deflection.": "",
  "2L^2/pi": "",
  "0": "",
  "L^2/pi": "",
  "L^2/(2pi)": "",
  "Let u = x, dv = sin(pi*x/L) dx. Then v = -(L/pi)cos(pi*x/L). Integral = [-(xL/pi)cos(pi*x/L)] from 0 to L + (L/pi) integral from 0 to L of cos(pi*x/L) dx = L^2/pi + (L/pi)[(L/pi)sin(pi*x/L)] from 0 to L = L^2/pi + 0 = L^2/pi.": "",
  "A machine depreciates in value at a rate of V'(t) = -1000 * t * e^(-0.2t) dollars per year. Using integration by parts, find the total depreciation from year 0 to year 5.": "",
  "25000(1 - 2e^(-1)) - 25000(e^(-1) - 1) dollars": "",
  "1000[25 - 50e^(-1)] dollars in depreciation": "",
  "-5000(-5e^(-1) + 25e^(-1) - 25) = -5000(20e^(-1) - 25) dollars": "",
  "-1000[5(-5e^(-1)) - 25(e^(-1) - 1)] dollars": "",
  "Total depreciation = integral from 0 to 5 of 1000*t*e^(-0.2t) dt. Let u = t, dv = e^(-0.2t) dt, v = -5e^(-0.2t). Integral = 1000{[-5t*e^(-0.2t)] from 0 to 5 + 5 integral from 0 to 5 of e^(-0.2t) dt} = 1000{-25e^(-1) + 5[-5e^(-0.2t)] from 0 to 5} = 1000{-25e^(-1) - 25e^(-1) + 25} = 1000(25 - 50e^(-1)).": "",
  "A runner's speed at time t minutes is v(t) = t * cos(t/10) meters per minute. Using integration by parts, set up and evaluate the distance traveled from t = 0 to t = 10 minutes (use integration by parts formula).": "",
  "100 sin(1) + 100(cos(1) - 1) meters": "",
  "100 sin(1) meters": "",
  "100(1 - cos(1)) meters": "",
  "10 cos(1) meters": "",
  "Distance = integral from 0 to 10 of t*cos(t/10) dt. Let u = t, dv = cos(t/10) dt, v = 10 sin(t/10). Integral = [10t sin(t/10)] from 0 to 10 - 10 integral from 0 to 10 of sin(t/10) dt = 100 sin(1) - 10[-10 cos(t/10)] from 0 to 10 = 100 sin(1) + 100(cos(1) - 1).": "",
  "A radioactive substance decays and its activity level is A(t) = (t + 1) * e^(-t) millicuries at time t years. Using integration by parts, find the cumulative activity from t = 0 to t = 3 years.": "",
  "2 + 5e^(-3) millicurie-years": "",
  "3e^(-3) millicurie-years": "",
  "1 - 4e^(-3) millicurie-years": "",
  "2 - 5e^(-3) millicurie-years": "",
  "Integral from 0 to 3 of (t+1)*e^(-t) dt = integral of t*e^(-t) dt + integral of e^(-t) dt. For the first: u = t, dv = e^(-t) dt gives [-t*e^(-t)] from 0 to 3 + integral of e^(-t) dt = -3e^(-3) + [-e^(-t)] from 0 to 3. Total = -3e^(-3) + (-e^(-3) + 1) + (-e^(-3) + 1) = 2 - 5e^(-3).": ""
